  "text": "Northern hybridization and reverse transcriptase-mediated PCR (RT-PCR). Northern hybridization was carried out by following standard procedures [CITATION_1] . For reverse transcription, an oligonucleotide hybridizing to the 3Ј end of 16S rRNA was used to prime the synthesis of cDNA. One microgram of the total RNA was used as the template, and reverse transcription was carried out as described in the instructions of the supplier of the RT (New England Biolabs, Inc., Beverly, Ma.). One microliter of the reverse transcription mix was used directly as the template in subsequent PCRs. A 50-l PCR mixture contains 10 pmol of each of two primers, 200 M each dATP, dGTP, dCTP, and dTTP, 1 U of Taq DNA polymerase (Amersham), and 1ϫ buffer provided with the Taq polymerase. The PCR program consisted of 20 cycles of 95°C for 40 s, 50°C for 30 s, and 72°C for 20 s. The PCR products were examined on a 1.2% agarose gel.",
